## A 96% Failure Rate: Moonlight Packing Corporation Takes the Cake

Among the companies that have made food recalls a nearly predictable occurrence, Moonlight Packing Corporation stands out--or falls, depending on your viewpoint. With a score of 96, the brand has achieved the dubious distinction of an "F" grade in food safety standards. That's right: a failure rate that rivals the most poorly graded exams. Yet, they're not alone in this club of ignominy. Albertsons Companies LLC and Ambriola Co., Inc. join them with similarly dismal scores of 94 and 89 respectively.

## A Year in Numbers

2026 is shaping up to be a record year for food recalls. With 302 incidents reported so far, the year is projected to surpass previous totals in no time. Breaking it down further, there have been 84 Class I recalls--indicative of situations where there is a reasonable probability of serious health consequences--and 193 Class II recalls, where the health risk is not immediately life-threatening but still worrisome. Class III recalls, while less severe, account for 25 cases this year.

## Repeat Offenders

A startling statistic reveals that there are 64 repeat offenders--brands that have had multiple recalls. This raises serious questions about the efficacy of the protective measures they claim to implement. Notable names like CHETAK NEW YORK LLC and Made Fresh Salads Inc. grace the list of shame.

## Top Offenders and Their Crimes

Examining the recent recalls paints a picture of negligence and oversight. The Maros Group, LLC recalled its Prickly Pear Jelly due to undeclared milk, while Lone Star Dairy Products LLC reported Salmonella contamination in spray-dried dairy powder. JFE Franchising Inc. appears twice for foreign objects, specifically glass, found in dumpling products. On the less severe end, Pocas International Corp. has packaging integrity issues with its popping boba teas.

## What This Means for Consumers

The statistics and repeated appearances of certain brands in recall notices indicate systemic issues in food safety protocols. Brands like Moonlight Packing Corporation and Albertsons Companies LLC need to step up their quality controls to avoid the health risks their products pose to the public.

## The Way Forward

Accountability and transparency are key. Brands must take responsibility for their failures and commit to robust measures that prevent recalls rather than responding to them. Consumers, too, play a role by staying informed and demanding higher standards.

## Closing Thoughts

This week's analysis underscores the importance of vigilance in the food industry. With a surge in recalls and repeat offenders topping the list, the message is clear: we need better systems to protect the public from preventable hazards. Until then, stay informed and choose wisely.
